 This README will outline the steps needed to build and execute qnn-sample-app. It is currently available to be built
 and executed on linux-x86_64, aarch64-android and arm-android platforms.

 Setup:
 ------

 Building qnn-sample-app has three external dependencies:
    1. clang compiler
    2. flatbuffers (flatbuffers compiler and development headers)
    3. ndk-build (for Android targets only)

 If the first two dependencies are not installed or available in your system PATH, the script check-linux-dependency.sh
 provided with the SDK can be used to install and prepare your environment. Alternatively, you could install these
 dependencies and make them available in your PATH.

 Command to automatically install required dependencies:
        $ source <SDK_ROOT>/target/x86_64-linux-clang/bin/check-linux-dependency.sh

 For the third dependency to be satisfied, ANDROID_NDK_ROOT needs to be set:
        $ export ANDROID_NDK_ROOT=<PATH-TO-NDK>

 Note: qnn-sample-app has been verified to work with Android NDK version r19c.

 Build:
 ------

 Once the setup is complete, the sample app can be built as follows:
        $ cd <SDK_ROOT>/examples/SampleApp
        $ make

 After executing make from above, you should be able to see two new folders in the same directory:
    1. bin: will contain qnn-sample-app binaries for each platform within respective directories.
    2. obj: this folder will contain all the object files that were used for building and linking the executable.

 To delete all the artifacts that were generated in the above step, run:
        $ cd <SDK_ROOT>/examples/SampleApp
        $ make clean

 Run:
 ----

 qnn-sample-app executable generated in the build step can be used to execute a model using any QNN backend available
 for linux-x86_64, aarch64-android and arm-android platforms. It is very similar to executing qnn-net-run. Refer to the
 general QNN documentation available at <SDK_ROOT>/Doc/general/tools.html to see how to run qnn-net-run. Simply
 replacing qnn-net-run with qnn-sample-app in the tutorials should help.

 For more tool help, run:
        $ qnn-sample-app --help
